data.name: label1.Text
data.value:
This program simulates the flow of patients through an ER in a typical day. For the porpose of having an effective simulation, hours are repesented as minutes and minutes as seconds.
Average patient arival delay: The two values to be entered are the minimum and maximum delay between patients arriving in minutes. The number at the end is the average delay between patients.
Percent chance per severity: The four values here represent the make up and distribution of patients in different categories. Rating 1 is a minor injury while a rating 4 is a life or death emergency. Each value is a percentage saying how many patients, out of 100, are in each category. As such the four values should add to 100.
Number of available rooms: This number represents how many patients can be treated at the same time. A larger value will often result in rooms not being used whereas a smaller value will result in long wait times.
Average room time: The values here represent the average amount of time, in minutes, that patint will need to be in a room while they are treated. Each values is in relation with rating as with the "Percent chance per severity."
Shift length: The shift length represents the amount of time, in hours, that the hospital will be recieving new patients. After the time is completed the program will room the remaining petients and end displaying the results.
Timed and Instant simulation buttons: The buttons will run the simulation with the specifications described above. The timed simulation will show the flow of patients to visualize the process. The instant simulation will quickly calculate the results and display them.
